ce:section.ce:para:
Recently, numerous techniques for detecting Al3+ or morin have been proposed, such as inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometry (ICP-MS), electrochemistry, high-performance liquid chromatography (HLPC), atomic emission spectrometry (AES) and atomic absorption spectrometry (AAS) [7–11]. Given the drawbacks of these traditional methods, such as the prolonged analysis time, the need of skilled personnel, costly instrumentation and elaborate sample preparation procedures, many researchers have devoted considerable resources in developing analytical approaches for morin and Al3+ 
                     [12]. Notably, the fluorometry using graphene quantum dots (GQDs) or carbon dots (CDs) has attracted much attention owing to their superior material performances, including solubility in many solvents, excellent fluorescence brightness, good photostability, biological compatibility and abundant functional groups [13,14]. To date, many examples exist for the detection of morin or Al3+. Liu et al. utilized glycine and urea as precursors to prepare the CDs via a green microwave irradiation method for morin determination from 0.4 to 60 μM with a limit of detection (LOD) of 0.12 μM within 30 min [15]. Mei et al. employed fifty-four eucommia ulmoides to synthesize CDs for Al3+ detection from 0.01 to 2.5 μM, achieving the LOD of 0.32 μM [16]. Yan et al. synthesized the carbon quantum dots functionalized with amino acids hydrothermally for selective detection of Al3+ in the range of 1–20 μM with the LOD of 0.32 μM [17]. Although these methods have quantitatively detected morin or Al3+ through fluorometry, they still lack the practicability and real-time capability. Additionally, there is a scarcity of methods capable of detecting two substances simultaneously, and their detection performances still have room for improvement. Consequently, it is highly desired to develop an effective, real-time and simple analytical “One Stone Two Birds” strategy for the simultaneous detection of morin and Al3+. See (Scheme 1
                     ).
